title: For Sale/Trade:  Hungarian PA-63 (matching serials/upgraded springs/ammo)
postcontent:
I have for trade/sale a Hungarian PA-63 with all matching serials. The stock 11 Lb. recoil spring has been upgraded to a Wolff 15 Lb to tame the formerly stout recoil the 9x18 has when mixed with the lightweight aluminum/titanium alloy frame of the PA-63.
It also has an upgraded Wolff 13 Lb. hammer spring that makes the DA trigger pull much nicer. A new firing pin spring was also installed.
The gun has functioned 100% with the upgrades, even with reduced power reloads and surplus ammo with hard primers that give other guns problems.

This firearm has a fixed barrel and is capable of some impressive accuracy if you do your part. I've also seen threaded barrels and .380 conversions available if that's interesting to you...but the 9x18 is more powerful than the .380 and in my opinion is also more accurate.
If you reload, this cartridge is a dream...you can trim 9x19 brass and load up some nice reduced power FMJ practice rounds or full power defensive loads using Hornady XTP bullets.

This will also come with a little over 200 rounds of ammo, a holster, a padded case, and a lock.

SGM tri rail hanguard, VFG, VT Flashlight mount and Surefire G2L light, SAW grip, 4 position gas regulator, Tromix Shark breacher brake, Tromix Bolt on knurled charging handle knob, couple reduced power action spring for shooting light loads.

All NFA rules apply.   (per the NFA [National Firearms Act] if you want to buy this gun as a SBS, you will have to send a "Form 4" along w/ $200 to the Federal Government & pass a background check.  When they send the form back approved several months later, you could then take possession of the gun.)

title: For Sale:  Two Tactical Backpacks--SO Tech Paladin Mission Pack and 5.11 Rush 72--$85 each!
postcontent:
Up for grabs are two packs--either one for $85 face-to-face:

-- A brand-new-with-tags black SO Tech Paladin Mission Pack Expedition

-- A lightly used 5.11 Rush 72 in Sandstone (I think). 

I bought several bags trying to figure out what I'd use for my hunting pack--lots of knee and shoulder problems/surgeries making me redefine how to manage getting to and from the field. Figured out what to use and now time to clear out the rest.

These packs are both right around $150-160 new (SO Tech IS new). 

SO Tech Paladin is no longer made (the SO Tech version runs around $400). The SO Tech bag has a plastic back support insert and expands from a 3-Day to a 5-Day pack. It's covered in MOLLE / PALS webbing to add whatever you need to add and it's designed to hold your Mission Go Bag in the front pocket if you have one (see pics; Mission Go Bag not included). Paladin is the affordable version of SO Tech's gear. It's made in Taiwan (like Maxpedition gear) to keep prices down, but does not skimp on quality in terms of materials, zippers, etc. The pack is guaranteed for life, just like any other SO Tech pack. I have both SO Tech and Paladin gear and notice no difference in terms of quality. Here's the link to the pack on the SO Tech website:

http://sotechtactical.com/products/paladin-mission-pack-expedition

The 5.11 Rush is a fantastically organized bag with pockets everywhere. It's set up for a water bladder (not provided), has a stuff sack in the front, and I THINK the waist pack tucks into the back. It is an amazing pack in every way. It was the runner up for me, but it was a close second (I ended up going with a Camelbak BFM). This one was lightly used by the previous owner and there are a couple of light dirt marks on it and one small light red mark--couldn't get pics of it in the light tonight at home. Other than that, it's in great shape--no real wear or tear on the bag. One day I'll probably buy this pack again, spend more on it than I'm selling it for, and resent the fact, but right now just looking for the cash! 

Specs for the pack are here:

http://www.511tactical.com/rush-72-backpack.html

Cash only; no Sunday sales.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ruger Mark III 22/45 with threaded barrel
location: north metro, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
This is an extremely accurate and fun firearm. 
The gun and everything included are in excellent to brand new condition.
Comes with a nice optical sight with 4 different patterns, 2 different colors (red or green) each with 3 different brightness levels. Extra batteries for the optical.
It has a threaded barrel and the end cap protector.
Comes with 2 Ruger factory magazines.
Ruger factory carrying/protective bag.
Brand new lockable carrying case with protective foam inside. I know a lot of people like to lock up their firearms when not using them and it's a great way to bring it home.

Other than the optical (which you can remove with just an allen wrench) it is exactly how it came from the factory with no "kitchen table gunsmithing" to the sear, trigger, springs, etc, etc - but there are MANY different things you can do to the internals of this handgun to fine tune it if you so choose; which is why I bought it in the first place but I never got around to it because it was already a tack driver so I didn't want to mess with it.
There are SO MANY different grips and other accessories you can get from Amazon, Ebay, Midway, etc if you want to dress it up and personalize this fun gun - literally 1000's of different options.
Although the Ruger looks and seems brand new, it isn't. I've shot exactly 200 rounds through it and they all performed flawlessly. Very fun gun to shoot. Most of the regular velocity rounds act like subsonic rounds (less than 1,100+ feet per second) due to the 4.5 inch barrel versus the long barrels on rifles, which is nice if you're trying to keep your shooting a bit quieter. 

I have several thousand rounds of various .22LR (FMJ and HP various brands, weights and speeds) that I'd be willing to sell or include with a trade for fair prices, not super inflated prices like you sometimes find lately.

I'm selling this gun because I just don't get out and shoot anymore.

I might be interested in trades and I can add money on my end if needed.
I'd for sure be interested in firewood (hardwood) that is seasoned & preferably split.

I live in Blaine but drive all over the Twin Cities for work and can most likely meet you pretty close to wherever is convenient for you.

Perfect gun for someone that is disabled, or has difficulty racking a slide (elderly, those with arthritis, small women etc...). You never rack the slide to shot this gun. You just drop a round in the tip up barrel, and once fired, it automatically cycles the next round. For a â€œmouseâ€ gun, it has a large 8+1 capacity. Taurus also makes a small caliber tip barrel design, but has a much heavier trigger (due to being double action). The Beretta is only single action, (where the hammer resets due to the blowback from the fired cartridge, and not from pulling the trigger â€“ The trigger only releases the hammer, which equals a light and smooth trigger). Very nice aged look. Nice, and small for concealed carry. Carry it with Hornady â€œmagicâ€ bullets, and it will be just as effective as a 40 caliber. I already have two (2) good shooting .25 acp caliber guns, and can't really justify keeping this one. Own a classic Beretta for only $210. Private sale. Must be over 21, have a Florida D/L and be legally able to own a firearm. Sale will must take place at my office in Palm Harbor. Don't waste my time if you are not willing to sign a bill of sale, or won't allow me to make a copy of your Florida d/license. If you want to spend a little less, I am willing to keep the Beretta, and would sell one of my Ravens that is in like new condition (with box), with only about 150 rds through it for $140.00. I never had any type of malfunction/misfire with the Raven.
